# Q-SYS Lua Script Architecture

## No OOP / Class Pattern

Every Q-SYS control script is a **singleton by nature**. Each script runs in its own context, binds to its own named controls via `Controls.*`, and discovers its own components via `Component.GetComponents()`. There is never more than one instance of a given controller per script context.

**Do not use class-based OOP** (`setmetatable`, `__index`, `.new()`, `self:`, `self.`). It adds ceremony with no benefit.

```lua
-- ❌ AVOID - unnecessary class machinery
MyController = {}
MyController.__index = MyController
function MyController.new() ... return setmetatable({}, MyController) end
function MyController:setRoute(input, output) ... end
myController = MyController.new()

-- ✅ CORRECT - flat module with local state
local components = { extronRouter = nil, invalid = {} }
local state = { power = false }

local function setRoute(input, output, source) ... end

init()
```

## Component Discovery

Each script calls `Component.GetComponents()` for itself. Scripts do not share instances or pass component references between each other via OOP inheritance — they call into a **public API table** exposed as a global.

```lua
-- Public surface for external scripts to call into
MatrixController = {
    setSource  = setSource,
    setRoute   = setRoute,
    cleanup    = cleanup,
}
```

## Standard Structure (all .lua scripts)

```
[ Controls ]      -- Controls.* snapshot
[ Utilities ]     -- isArr, setProp, bind, bindArray, cleanupComponentHandlers
[ Config ]        -- debugging, clearString, roomName, componentTypes, input/output maps
[ State ]         -- components {}, state {}, uci {}, norm {}
[ Debug ]         -- debugPrint()
[ Functions ]     -- local function, forward-declared with local where needed
[ Events ]        -- registerEvents()
[ Init ]          -- init() with === phase markers
[ Public API ]    -- GlobalName = { exposed functions }
[ Start ]         -- pcall(init)
```

## When OOP Would Be Appropriate

Only if a script genuinely needs **multiple independent instances within the same file** (e.g., a reusable display driver managing 8 distinct displays with fully isolated state). This has not been needed in any current project script.
